### File Handling in Rust

The `std::fs` module provides functions for file and filesystem operations. Combined with `std::io`, it enables comprehensive file manipulation.

---

### Key Types

| Type | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `File` | Represents an open file |
| `Path` / `PathBuf` | Filesystem paths |
| `DirEntry` | Directory entry |
| `Metadata` | File metadata |

---

### Common File Operations

```rust
use std::fs;
use std::path::Path;

// File existence
if Path::new("file.txt").exists() {
    println!("File exists");
}

// Copy, rename, remove
fs::copy("source.txt", "dest.txt")?;
fs::rename("old.txt", "new.txt")?;
fs::remove_file("temp.txt")?;

// Directory operations
fs::create_dir("new_dir")?;
fs::create_dir_all("a/b/c")?;  // recursive
fs::remove_dir("empty_dir")?;
fs::remove_dir_all("dir_tree")?;  // recursive

// Metadata
let metadata = fs::metadata("file.txt")?;
println!("Size: {} bytes", metadata.len());
println!("Is file: {}", metadata.is_file());
println!("Is dir: {}", metadata.is_dir());
```

> **Key Point:** Most file operations return `Result` types and require error handling. Use `fs::create_dir_all` for recursive directory creation. Path operations are platform-independent via the `Path` type.

codeExample:
use std::fs;
use std::path::Path;

fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    // Check if file exists
    let config_path = Path::new("config.json");
    if config_path.exists() {
        println!("Config file found");
        let metadata = fs::metadata(config_path)?;
        println!("Size: {} bytes", metadata.len());
    } else {
        println!("Config file not found");
    }

    Ok(())
}
